A RESOLUTION
1 Honoring the life and memory of the Honorable Vincent D. Fort; and for other purposes.
2 WHEREAS, the State of Georgia mourns the loss of one of its most distinguished citizens
3 with the passing of the Honorable Vincent D. Fort on December 22, 2024; and
4 WHEREAS, the Honorable Vincent D. Fort was born on April 28, 1956, in New Britain,
5 Connecticut, a beloved son of Charles Fort Sr. and Clara Hutchinson Fort; and
6 WHEREAS, after completing his higher education, he settled in Atlanta, Georgia, where he
7 became a respected historian, taught at Morehouse College and Morris Brown College, and
8 served as assistant director of the Martin Luther King Jr. Papers Project; and
9 WHEREAS, the Honorable Vincent D. Fort further served as a Georgia State Senator for the
10 39th District from 1996 to 2017, representing parts of Atlanta, East Point, College Park,
11 Union City, and unincorporated Fulton County as well as consistently advocating for justice
12 and equity; and
13 WHEREAS, in 2001, the Honorable Vincent D. Fort authored Georgia's first hate crimes
14 law, ensuring harsher penalties for crimes motivated by bias, followed by the passage of the
